<http://model.geneontology.org/5993df9e00000254> a owl:Ontology ;
    ns2:modelstate "review"^^xsd:string ;
    dc:contributor "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3898-1727"^^xsd:string ;
    dc:date "2023-03-16"^^xsd:string ;
    dc:title "SynGO no. 1f GLS2_PMID:24121663"^^xsd:string ;
    ns1:providedBy "http://www.ucl.ac.uk/functional-gene-annotation/cardiovascular"^^xsd:string,
        "https://www.ucl.ac.uk/functional-gene-annotation/neurological/projects/tabs/syngo-ucl"^^xsd:string ;
    ns3:id "gomodel:5993df9e00000254"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment """Abstract:
"The amino acid Glutamine is converted into Glutamate by a deamidation reaction catalyzed by the enzyme Glutaminase (GLS). Two isoforms of this enzyme have been described, and the GLS2 isoform is regulated by the tumor suppressor gene p53. Here, we show that the p53 family member TAp73 also drives the expression of GLS2. Specifically, we demonstrate that TAp73 regulates GLS2 during retinoic acid-induced terminal neuronal differentiation of neuroblastoma cells, and overexpression or inhibition of GLS2 modulates neuronal differentiation and intracellular levels of ATP. Moreover, inhibition of GLS activity, by removing Glutamine from the growth medium, impairs in vitro differentiation of cortical
neurons. Finally, expression of GLS2 increases during mouse cerebellar development. Although, p73 is dispensable for the in vivo expression of GLS2, TAp73 loss affects GABA and Glutamate levels in cortical neurons. Together, these findings suggest a role for GLS2 acting, at least in part, downstream of p73 in neuronal differentiation and highlight a possible role of p73 in regulating neurotransmitter synthesis.\""""^^xsd:string,
        "Automated change 2022-04-14: <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CL_0002609> replaced_by <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CL_0010012>",
        "Automated change 2023-03-16: RO:0002213 replaced by RO:0002629",
        """Species Confirmation Request:
Kramarz, Barbara
   |
Yesterday, 18:02
ma285@leicester.ac.uk 
Dear Professor Agostini,

I am a gene ontology (GO) biocurator at the University College London and the focus of my current project, funded by Alzheimer's Research UK, is on annotating gene products involved in neurological disorders.  

Within your paper PMID:24121663 (Velletri et al., 2013) you demonstrate the roles of GLS2 and p73 in neuronal differentiation.   

A critical piece of information, which we require to annotate published data is species information.    

Could you please confirm the species of origin of the GPF-tagged GLS2 construct used in the neurite outgrowth assay presented in Figure 2?     

With verification of the species, the annotations of your findings will be able to be included in the GO database (e.g [QuickGO link to one of the human genes you list above/http://www.ebi.ac.uk/QuickGO/GProtein?ac=Q9Y4P3]), which will make them available in other major public biological databases, including NCBI-Gene, Ensembl and UniProt.   

I will look forward to hearing from you.  

Kind Regards, 
Barbara

-----

Barbara_Kramarz,_PhD  ||  Gene_Ontology_Biocurator  ||  Functional_annotation_of_proteins_and_microRNAs

UCL Rayne Building,  5_University_Street,  London_WC1E_6JF  ||  Tel.:_+44(0)2076796965   ||   Ext.: 46965   ||  Skype: bkramarz307
||  http://www.ucl.ac.uk/functional-gene-annotation  ||  Twitter:_@UCLgene """^^xsd:string,
        """To do next week:
Update model from 'development' to 'review' after inclusion of the isoform annotations. 
If authors ever confirm the species of GLS2 in the GFP construct, then could also add another evidence code (direct assay evidence used in manual assertion) to the 'regulation of neuron projection development' annotation, but do not wait for it."""^^xsd:string,
        "To do next week: Make the isoform specific annotations. Re: https://github.com/geneontology/noctua-models/issues/36"^^xsd:string ;
    ns6:in_taxon ns4:NCBITaxon_9606 .

